<body>

<h1>@HI{{dai}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<dl>
<dt>(A)
<ol>
<li> @Ana{{}} <strong>@HI{{dai}}</strong>
<li> @N{{}} <strong>@HI{{dai}}</strong>
</ol>
<dt>(B)
<ol>
<li> @Vplain{{}} @HI{{nn}} <strong>@HI{{dai}}</strong>
<li> @Ai{{}} @HI{{nn}} <strong>@HI{{dai}}</strong>
<li> @Ana{{}} @HI{{nn}} <strong>@HI{{dai}}</strong>
<li> @N{{}} @HI{{nann}} <strong>@HI{{dai}}</strong>
</ol>
</dl>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{dai}}</strong> is a sentence-final particle which is used in informal male speech to mark a WH-question.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{dokoga@KJ{{quiet}}ka<strong>dai</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      What place is quiet?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
When <strong>@HI{{dai}}</strong> is used with a question, it must be an interrogative one:
<a href="grammar-particle-kai.html">@HI{{kai}}</a> is used with yes-no questions.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{dai}}</strong> is actually the <a href="grammar-copula.html">da</a> followed by @HI{{i}}, so it can only
follow @HI{{na}}-adjectives and nouns. It can follow @HI{{i}}-adjectives and verbs if the form <strong>@HI{{ndai}}</strong>
as the @HI{{nn}} is an abbreviation of the nominaliser <a href="grammar-no-nominaliser.html">@HI{{no}}</a>.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{dai}}</strong> cannot be used for "yes/no" questions, only WH questions. For "yes/no" questions,
@HI{{kai}} is used instead.
</p>

